%section#grid_arguments
  %header.toadstool_subheader
    %h2 grid arguments
    %article
      %p
        Additional arguments can be passed into the grid mixin to include
        %code $grid_padding_l, $grid_padding_r, $grid_padding_tb, $grid_border, $grid_uom, $col_gutter, $grid_type, $grid_align, $grid_context
      %ul
        %li
          %code $grid_padding_l
          %span adds padding LEFT, takes integer value
        %li
          %code $grid_padding_r
          %span adds padding RIGHT, takes integer value
        %li
          %code $grid_padding_tb
          %span adds padding TOP and BOTTOM, takes integer value
        %li
          %code $grid_border
          %span takes integer value, adds border using
          %code $border_color
          and
          %code $standard_border_style
          configs found in
          = succeed "." do
            %code _config.scss
        %li
          %code $border_place
          %span options are
          %code left
          and
          = succeed "." do
            %code right
          Argument will place a single border on either the left or right side of the block.
        %li
          %code $grid_uom
          %span set to percent by default, accepts
          %code em
          as argument.
        %li
          %code $col_gutter
          %span takes integer to adjust col gutter
        %li
          %code $grid_type
          %span set to 12 col by default, allows for on-the-fly adjustment to grid type
          %b Feature is currently inoperable
        %li
          %code $grid_align
          %span takes
          %code center
          as argument
        %li
          %code $grid_context
          %span Adjusts column widths based on nested grid context. Necessary when calcuclating with percentages
      %p
        Stipe uses the
        %code box-size
        CSS property, but this is not supported by IE7. By entereing values like
        = succeed "," do
          %code $grid_padding_l, $grid_padding_r, $grid_border
        Stipe will calculate a width that IE7 can use.
